raft, for free and used for non-commercial purposes. It is not allowed to copy it, modify it, translate it or anything similar.\n\nChapter 1: The archaeological evidence of early Islam\n\nIntroduction The historical evidence of early Islam. If you haven't yet researched the true history of the Quran, this chapter will definitely amaze you, some which only in recent years have emerged.\n\nQibla (archaeological evidence) Creswell and Fehervari went to middle-east in 1905 to look for evidence for the earliest mosques from 600th AD – early 800th AD and where their qibla pointed at. They found out the following: • Wassit mosque (706 AD, Iraq) – Qibla facing Jerusalem (But in truth facing between Petra and Mecca) It does not face Mecca • Kufa mosque (Iraq) – Qibla facing to Jerusalem (in truth west to PETRA) It does not face south to Mecca • Fustat mosque (641 AD, Cairo) – Qibla facing Jerusalem (in truth PETRA) It does not face south to Mecca They concluded they all face to Jerusalem, but in reality they faced to Petra, and Wassit mosque faced between Petra and Mecca, but closer to Petra. Dan Gibson used satellite images to determine the direction of earliest mosques because it became forbidden to visit them. The conclusion is as follows: • • • • • • •\n\nMasjid al-Qiblatayn (623 AD, Saudi Arabia) - Original qibla faced PETRA It was rebuilt to face Mecca Great Mosque of Guangzhou (627 AD, China) – Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Al Mudhmar Mosque (627 AD, Oman) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Hama Great Mosque (637 AD, Syria) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Palmyra Mosque (640 AD, Syria) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Humeima mosque (Jordan) – Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Dome of the Rock (691 AD, Jerusalem) – Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca\n\n23\n\n• • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • • •\n\n24\n\nAqaba Umayyad Mosque (600-699 AD, Jordan) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Qasr Mushash (600-699 AD, Jordan) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Massawa Mosque (600-699 AD, Eritrea) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Jerash Umayyad Mosque (700 AD, Jordan) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Great Mosque of Ba’albek (701 AD, Lebanon) – Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Amman Citadel (701 AD, Jordan) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Great Mosque of Sana’a (705 AD, Yemen) – Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Khirbit al Minya (706 AD, Israel) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Al Aqsa Mosque (706 AD, Jerusalem) – Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Masjid al-Tarik Khana (708 AD, Israel) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Damascus Mosque (709 AD, Syria) – Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Um Walid (712 AD, Israel) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Qasr Qastal (720 AD, Israel) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Mosque of Umar (720 AD, Syria) – Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Khirbat al Mafjar (724 AD, Israel) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Anjar Mosque (724 AD, Lebanon) – Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Siraf Early Mosque (750 AD, Iron) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Malek Mosque (780 AD, Iran) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Sahi Ramdah Mosque (700-799, Oman) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Qiblatain Mosque (700-799, Oman) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca\n\n25\n\n• • • •\n\nAl-Sawaf Mosque Grounds (700-799, Iraq) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Bibi-Khanym Mosque (700-799, Uzbekistan) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca Ulugh Beg Mosque (700-799 AD, Uzbekistan) - Qibla faceing PETRA It does not face Mecca Magokki Attor Mosque (800-899 AD, Uzbeckistan) - Qibla facing PETRA It does not face Mecca\n\nThere are even additional examples which are neither facing Mecca or Petra but in between, for example the Yamana mosque in Saudi Arabia. All Qiblas which were newly built were facing Petra until 706 AD. The first one to be built which faced Mecca was in Banbhore, Pakistan on 727 AD, finally 105 years after it was revealed in Surah 2:143-145. Later in this chapter, it is mentioned that Mecca was not even referenced until 741 AD in historical documents. That is 109 years after Muhammad died. Patricia Crone, who could speak 15 languages, went throughout the entire arabian peninsula and could not find Mecca being mentioned anywhere in the 7th century, but first found it mentioned in Continuatio Byzantia Arabica in 741 AD. She went throughout all the trading documents and concluded that Mecca was not even in the caravan trade route, but Petra was the center of that. Furthermore there are no maps where Mecca was mapped in until much later in 900 AD, that means you cannot find any map with Mecca on it until about 300 years after Muhammad’s death. Even the first reference for Islam is from 691 AD. The sanctuary in Petra was destroyed by an earthquake in 713 AD, and this might be a reason by they changed the center of Islam to Mecca, because God wouldn't create an earthquake in the center of Islam. Sahih al-Bukhari 23:432 - The Prophet said, \"Allah has made Mecca a sanctuary (sacred place) and it was a sanctuary before me and will be so after me. The problem is that to date there are no ancient trees that have ever existed in Mecca. In the construction industry, you have to have archaeologists when you have to dig up a foundation for new buildings, and very often there are archaeological evidence. However in Mecca no ruins of ancient cities was ever found.\n\n26\n\nThe accuracy of the direction of the Qiblas Before Dan Gibson determined over 100 of the earliest mosques, it was believed that those few known Qiblas actually showed that they are just inaccurate directions made during the beginning of the Islamic era. Thus it would seem that there should be many mosque which pointed in many directions, possibly 20 or more different directions. However, this is not the case, as all those early mosques only pointed at 4 different Qiblas: Petra, between Petra and Mecca, parallel and finally Mecca. The timeline can be seen below\n\nWhat is interesting is that the accuracy of the Qiblas for the first three are more accurate than for Mecca, as shown below: City Petra Between Parallel Mecca\n\nNumber of early mosques 20 20 6 10\n\nAccuracy (degrees) 2,9 degrees 0,98 degrees 3,5 degrees 4,78 degrees\n\nIf one takes out two of the worst Mosques from Petra, leaving 18 behind, the accuracy goes to 1,9 degrees. With only 4 Qiblas total, and all the other cities (Petra, between, parallel) are more accurate than Mecca, proves that people during 7th, 8th and 9th century were sophisticated enough to know how to calculate the direction, thus proving it was intentional. Furthermore, there is Humeima and Aqaba mosque, which are so close to Petra that calculating the direction with the help of the sun and stars are not needed. If it points to Petra, it is because it was intentional\n\n27\n\nRahat Mosque found in july 2019 In july 2019 a new small mosque was found in the city of Rahat dated to be built in 636 CE. The position of the mosque is directly in line with Petra and Mecca, so it's qibla faces both of them directly in a line. However, considering all the other mosque's mentioned, also in Israel, they all point to Petra from other parts of the lands which confirms that the intention of the Qibla of the Rahat mosque was not to face Mecca but Petra. For further study, read Early Islamic Qiblas: A survey of mosques built between 1AH/622 C.E. and 263 AH/876 C.E. by Dan Gibson (2017) and When Did the Qibla Change by Dan Gibson (2017). Dan Gibson used ASTER to determine the qibla It is often claimed that Dan Gibson used Google Maps or Google Earth to determine the qiblas of the early mosques from 7th-9th century. This is however not true, he used Advanced Thermal Emission and Reflection Radiometer (ASTER) sattelites, which is described on pages 115-120 in his book Early Islamic Qiblas, published in 2017. The ASTER data itself has been validated by NASA, METI, Japan's Earth Remote Sensing Data Analysis Center (ERSDAC), and the U.S. Geological Survey, and the U.S. National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency. Difference between planar and spherical Even though Dan Gibson would have used two-dimensional maps instead of ASTER satellites which takes the curvature of the earth into account, the spherical qibla and planar qibla would still almost be the same. This means spherical geometry is not necessary to come to the same conclusion that they still point at Petra. Taking the example with 600 km horizontal and 1000 km vertical. This can be achieved by first using the coordinates of Petra: • Latitude: 30.328960 • Longitude: 35.444832 In spherical geometry, 1 degree corresponds to 111,699 km. This means that 600 km to the east of Petra corresponds to 5,371 degrees, and 1000 km south from Petra corresponds to 8,9526 degrees. Adding those degrees to Petra, the new point becomes: • City longitude 35,444832 + 5,371 = 40,815832 E • City latitude 30,328960 - 8,9526 = 21,37632 N\n\n28\n\nNow the azimuth, which is the angle in a sphere, can be calculated by inserting two different coordinates, in this case Petra and the new city. Doing so will result in an azimuth of 332,8 degrees which is a difference of 27,2 degrees compared to the planar example of 30,9 degrees. The difference between the 30,9 degrees planar and 27,2 degrees spherical is 3,7 degrees. This means that the difference in spherical and planar is small due to the fact that 1000 km is only 2,5% of a sphere and it would not have a huge impact. Furthermore, the majority of mosques actually are less than 500 km away from Petra, so the difference would be less than 1,85 degrees between the spherical and planar, if not down to 0,2 degree. In short, even if Dan Gibson used twodimensional maps, it would not change the conclusion. The criticism by David King After Dan Gibson published his book about the early qiblas in 2017, David King, an astronomer who studied the mathematical history of the qiblas based on books written in the 8th, 9th, 10th, and even up to 11th century, criticised his qibla findings. However, much of his comments to Dan Gibson are wrong, because when it comes to the earliest mosques which points to Petra, three things needs to be done in order for it to be analysed fully: 1. Precisely determining the actual direction from the specific location of the mosque in one city to the center of Petra. This is called azimuth and can be calculated easily through different websites. This means mosques are not included in this calculation, only the location where the mosques has been built. This way the correct spherical angle from a specific location in a city to Petra is determined. This gives angle A, and is specifically the 100% correct angle and direction from one city to another. 2. Determining the qibla of the mosques by using its walls, and comparing it to the actual one. This is angle B. This angle is determined from only one location, the location of the mosques, specifically by using its walls. Dan Gibson used satellite images and GPS to precisely determine the Qibla and compared it to the actual ones. Note: It is important to note that all Dan Gibson did, was to measure how accurate the mosques were in the 7th, 8th and 9th century, which is angle B, by measuring the precise angle of the mosques walls and see where they were facing. This means that Dan Gibson didn't chose Petra - it chose him. Since all mosques until 706 AD faced around Petra, he then calculated the actual direction, by using the location of the mosques in question and the center of Petra. This way he\n\n29\n\ncalculated the deviation of how accurate the walls of the mosques were compared to the correct azimuth, which is the location of the city to Petra. So step 1 and step 2 above are only meant to to use modern techniques to accurately test how knowledgeable and precise the measurement and calculation of the Nabateans were. This is called presentism. 3. Determining the Qibla through ancient methods. This can be done by separating the vector direction into an X-component and Y-component. The Y-component is the latitude and the X-component is the longitude. This means that reproducing the qibla direction using ancient method, to test if it is possible to reproduce the same results - and if it is actually possible to built mosques with the knowledge of 7th century as precise as the actual azimuth. It requires an astrolabe, which measures the angle to the north star, and thereby the latitude. The astrolabe existed already in the Ancient Greece. Furthermore it requires a 100 meter rope and two persons. They will need to have a starting point where the mosque would be built. Person A extends the rope 100 meter fully to the north. Then person B takes the other end and extends it 100 meter in front of person A, again North. Then person A again goes in front of person B and extend it 100 meter again. By now they have measured it 300 meters north, which is the y-component, the latitude. They have to do it until they reach to the same angle as Petra, which is by using the astrolabe and measuring the altitude of the north star. When they reach to the same latitude as Petra, they just have to go straight east or straight west through a constant longitudinal direction, which is the X-component. This is called \"running down the easting\" or \"running down the westing\" and follow a line of constant latitude where the angle to the north star is constant. So what exactly is King's criticism? He is angry because he thinks that Dan Gibson wanted to compare point 2 with point 3 above, in which he thinks that Dan Gibson tried to reproduce the qibla direction by using modern techniques, satellite images and GPS. This is however not true. Dan Gibson wanted to measure and compare how accurate the Nabateans were in building the direction of the mosques to the actual direction to Petra, which is point 1 and point 2. David King doesn't believe the Arabs were sophisticated enough in the 7th century to built qiblas, so this is the reason why point 3 is important. Someone needs to finance people in order to reproduce point 3 manually, which is actually very easy to do be done very precisely. There is no doubt that anyone, even high school students, can reproduce the qibla direction with a high accuracy to Petra from any location in the Midde-East using ancient method, by only using an astrolabe or a quadrant, and some kind of a measurement or a rope. This would\n\n30\n\ndebunk any criticism that determining the qibla in the 7th century is actually possible with an high accuracy. This is basically what David Kings criticism is all about; Dan Gibson shouldn't reproduce the qibla using modern technology, but should go into the field and use only what was available at the time, namely the astrolabe or quadrant, and some kind of a rope measurement. When this gets done, whether by Dan Gibson or by anyone else, nobody cannot refute that the qibla was actually intended to be Petra until 706 AD, because the result will be very obvious for any person who has basic knowledge of mathematics and astronomy, that anyone can reproduce the qibla easily with high accuracy as the Nabateans in the 7th century. This is easily demonstrated when there are only 4 qiblas with an high accuracy, where the earlier qiblas in the 7th century were more accurate than the later qiblas in the 8th and 9th century. The Meccan qiblas from the 8th and 9th century are the least accurate. Building the Qibla mosque Let's say you have you go 1000 km north and then 600 km east \"running down the westing\" in order for reaching Petra, then you can scale down this perpendicular triangle to 10 meters north and 3 meters west. This means, you chose a point in your city, take a rope and extend it 10 meter north. Then take another rope and extend it meters to the left/west. This triangle has exactly the same direction/angle as the 1000km/600km, and it will face Petra correctly. You can also double it to 20 meter and 6 meters, because the further two points are the more precise it would become. This means you don't even need trigonometry or calculations, but by just using the logic of straight-angled triangles. This is why it is important to finance people to do it manually. If one goes 600 km east from Petra, and then 1000 km south, you'll end up in Ta'if, which is very close to Mecca (maybe 50 km or so). The azimuth from Ta'if to Petra is 332°45'36\", which is around 28 degrees, compared to the triangle which became 30,9 degrees. A 3,9 degrees difference. On the next page it has been illustrated. It was Eratosthenes (276-194 BC) who proposed the system of latitude and longitude for a map of the world, which is 800 years before Islam. Then Hipparchus (190-120 BC) was the first person to use this system and specify specific places on Earth. He furthermore was the first person to use time to determine the longitude. How ancient Nabateans navigated in pre-Islamic era Pliny the Elder (24-79 AD) wrote about how the Nabateans, who were the ancient Arabs, navigated 600 years before Islam in his Natural History, Vol 12, Chapter 32.\n\n31\n\n32\n\nThey measured the steps in order to know how to travel from one destination to another. He recorded from the Arabs that from Timna in Yemen to Gaza, it would take 2.437.500 steps to reach, which would take 62 days. For further study, read Arab Arab Navigation in the Indian Ocean Before the Coming of the Portuguese by G.R. Tibbetts (1971), and Pliny the Elder, Natural History, Translated by H. Rackham, London (1942). Date of construction They used many different means to find out the dates of the mosques. Mosques are usually the most important buildings in any given town or city, so they are well known and well documented. Therefore, some have inscriptions of their dates on them, as many important buildings even today do, others are written about in peoples annals, or are referred to in government documents. The dates they used, however, are not the dates we would use, as they commonly referred to the dates taken from the time the current ruler came to power. Two mosques at the Amman Citadal One of the most important mosques to confirm that the Qibla to Mecca was changed around 727 AD is the Amman Umayyad Mosque and Amman Umayyad Palace, which are located in Jordan, right beside each other. The first mosque mentioned was built in 701 AD and point towards Petra, and the second mosque mentioned was built in 730 AD which points towards Mecca. This confirms the previous that mosques started to point at Mecca between 701-730 AD. The latitude line The latitude line or the horizontal line is one of the most important evidence that the direction of the mosques were not wrongly placed. This is because the latitude line is a constant directional line through west and east and is perpendicular to the north star, which means it is 90 degrees. Pointing horizontal to the east eliminates the need for focusing unsystematically. If a mosque points straight to west or east, then it was intentional. This is the case with the Fustat mosque from Egypt which points almost directly to east to Petra, and not south to Mecca. This latitude line plays also a major role with the Sahi mosque, Qiblatain mosque, Al Mudhmar mosque, and Siraf Early Mosque which points above the horizontal line directly to Petra, and not below the horizontal line to Mecca. The longitude line The longitude line or vertical line is also an important evidence that demonstrates\n\n33\n\nthat the mosques intentionally faced Petra and not Mecca. Unlike the latitude line, the longitude line is only dependent straight of the north star. If a mosque points right of the north star, then it was intentional because it is very easy to build a qibla towards the right side of the north star - and the same can be applied to the left of the north star. This is very important because Massawa Mosque in Eritrea should be pointing to the right of the north star to Mecca, but it points to the left side, which is to Petra. Jacob of Odessa Jacob of Odessa was a Christian traveller and wrote traditional narrative of the Arabs, in which he calls them for Mahgraye, a Greek term used by the northern part of Arabia. He is an important part of confirming the date of construction of the mosques, because this confirms that the evolution of the mosques as illustrated earlier indeed gets confirmed by an eyewitness account in his writings in the 680s-705 AD. These letters are held in the British Museum today. While he was serving as a bishop in Odessa he accounts that the Jews prayed to the south from Fustat, Egypt, and the Arabs prayed to the east towards the Kaaba. As written earlier, Petra is almost directly east from Fustat. He also mentions that the Arabs living in the lands of Babel, Hillah and Basrah prayed to the west towards the Kaaba. Those places are all situated in Iraq. Interestingly enough, Basrah points directly west to Petra. If the Arabs had to pray to Mecca from those three places, they had to turn towards south-south-west, which is much closer to the south than to the west. For further study, read Hagarism: The Making of the Islamic World by Patricia Crone and Michael Cook (1977). The four cardinal points The four cardinal directions, also called the cardinal points, are the directions north, east, south and west. Every ancient civilization on Earth has independently used these four points, from Egyptian and Chinese cultures to the ancient Indians, from the Native Americans to European and Arabic cultures, to Aboriginal Australia. The Ancient Egyptians built the pyramids in Giza around 3000 years before Islam, and they had directed the pyramids to the north star with only a deviation of 0,067 degrees off. The Gate of the Sun, which is located in the city of Tiwanaku in western Bolivia, America is around 1500 years old, and its directions points straight to the cardinal points. Harappa, which is a archaeological site from 2600 BC in modern day Pakistan has its directions faced exactly to the four cardinal\n\n34\n\npoints. The Nabateans carved detailed architecture from the sandstone cliffs of mountains, with a very high precision of geometrical structures, thus they would have easily known the four cardinal directions, which is based on the location of the primary cardinal point, the north star. The latitude line or parallel north line contains two of the cardinal points, east and west. This is the reason why qiblas, for example Siraf Early Mosque in Iran, were not mistakes, because they point above the latitude line to Petra, closer to north-west, rather than below the latitude line to Mecca, which is in the south-western direction. Furthermore the architecture of the Petra rock buildings were borrowed by the Greeks and Romans, thus proving that they did had communication and therefore the possibility of the Nabateans to also borrow the knowledge of the quadrant to measure the altitude of the north star was definitely possible. One of the earliest evidences of a quadrant comes from the book Almagest, written by Ptolemy (100170 AD), in which he described measuring how he could measure the altitude of the noon sun on a 90 degree arc. The astrolabe, which is a more advanced tool than the quadrant, was invented by Hipparchus (190-120 BC). Both Theon of Alexandra (335-405 AD) and John Philoponus (490-570 AD) wrote a detailed treatise on it before Islam. The mesopotamian bshiop Severus Sebokht (575-667 AD) wrote a treatise on it in the Syriac language in the mid-7th century, which can be an indication that it was known in the northern part of the Arabian peninsula. The mosques point to Petra and not Jerusalem It is often claimed that the original qibla was Jerusalem, but this is certainly not true. The mosques which are right east of Jerusalem points south to Petra and not to the west to Jerusalem. Aqaba and Humeima are so close to Petra that you cannot be mistaken constructing the Qibla to Petra, and definitely not Mecca. Furthermore Fustat Mosque points straight to east to Petra, which is called running down the easting, and not to north-east to Jerusalem. All those three locations together prove that the original qibla was not Jerusalem. The evolution of the qiblas fits the timeline of the rulings The political tension between the Umayyad Caliphate, Abassid Caliphate and AlHajjaj fits perfectly in regards to the evolution of the qiblas. The Umayyad Caliphate ruled between 661-750, and their qibla was the same as the ancestors, which was towards Petra. Notice that the last known qibla for Petra\n\n35\n\nwas in 747 AD. Al-Hajjaj (reigned 705-714 AD) rebelled from the Ummayad Caliphate and the mosque between Petra and Mecca began pointing from 706-750 AD, which indicates that the qibla died with him. The Abbasid Caliphate began overpowering the ruling from 750-1258 AD, and the first known qibla towards Mecca was in 727 AD. All the three qiblas fits in the timeline of the political rulings of the different Caliphates and Al-Hajjaj. This is a clear indication that the qibla is a political direction and not a religious one. This is why the statement below sounds more of a political qibla: \"When the armies of Kufa met ibn Zubayr, Bujayr ibn 'Abdallah al Musli spoke: Praise be to God who has tested us with shackles and has tested you by your forgiving us. Ibn Zubayr, we are people who turn to the same Qibla as you.\" Tabari 21:112 Qibla pointing to other places than Mecca All mosques pointed to Petra until 701 AD according to Advanced Thermal Emission and Reflection Radiometer (ASTER), and the two mosques in Amman. You only need mosques till 700 AD to disprove Meccas existence in 7th century. You do not need 8th century and 9th century mosques, because they represent 8th century and 9th century. The qibla is mentioned in the Quran \"We have certainly seen the turning of your face, [O Muhammad], toward the heaven, and We will surely turn you to a qiblah with which you will be pleased. So turn your face toward al-Masjid al-haram. And wherever you [believers] are, turn your faces toward it [in prayer]. Indeed, those who have been given the Scripture well know that it is the truth from their Lord. And Allah is not unaware of what they do.\" - Quran 2:144\n\nBut the Quran doesn't mention from where to where the Qibla had changed in chapter 2. There are however some points to consider: • There are only 4 directions, and the accuracy of Petra, between and parallel are more accurate than for Mecca • There are Humeima mosque and Aqaba mosques which are so close to Petra\n\n36\n\nthat you don't even need astronomy to understand where to have its Qibla towards to. • The most important mosque of all of them is the Fustat mosque, because it has always been a known fact that if two cities had the same angle of the North Star then all they need to do is something called \"running down the easting\" or \"running down the westing\", either straight east or straight west. This means the direction is horizontal and eliminates the vertical axis (the y-axis). This is the clearest evidence that Petra was really the original city. Dan Gibson has however not included this point. • Regarding \"running down the easting\" and \"running down the westing\", when two cities are in the same angle, the qibla should point horizontally. Qibatain is a city that has almost the same angle as Mecca, and yet it doesn't point straight west, but north-west directly to Petra. In fact, Qibatains latitude is higher than Meccas and therefore it should point south-west. This means it should project below the horizontal line, and not north west as it does.\n\nDescription of Mecca In this section it will be discussed the problems with the description of Mecca which doesn't fit to the actual Mecca in history or today. There are many topics to cover, so is therefore important to separate them in parts. The Qibla was changed from unknown to Mecca Muhammad changed the Qibla in 624 AD, according to Quran 2:143-144 and Quran 2:149-150. It was at this time Muhammad waged war on the Jews and Christians, because they couldn't get along. \"And thus we have made you a just community that you will be witnesses over the people and the Messenger will be a witness over you. And We did not make the qiblah which you used to face except that We might make evident who would follow the Messenger from who would turn back on his heels. And indeed, it is difficult except for those whom Allah has guided. And never would Allah have caused you to lose your faith. Indeed Allah is, to the people, Kind and Merciful.\" Quran 2:143 \"We have certainly seen the turning of your face, [O Muhammad], toward the heaven, and We will surely turn you to a qiblah with which you will be pleased. So turn your face toward al-Masjid al-Haram. And wherever you [believers] are, turn your faces toward it [in prayer]. Indeed, those who have been given the Scripture\n\n37\n\nwell know that it is the truth from their Lord. And Allah is not unaware of what they do.\" - Quran 2:144 \"So from wherever you go out [for prayer, O Muhammad] turn your face toward al- Masjid al-Haram, and indeed, it is the truth from your Lord. And Allah is not unaware of what you do.\" - Quran 2:149 \"And from wherever you go out [for prayer], turn your face toward al-Masjid alHaram. And wherever you [believers] may be, turn your faces toward it in order that the people will not have any argument against you, except for those of them who commit wrong; so fear them not but fear Me. And [it is] so I may complete My favor upon you and that you may be guided.\" - Quran 2:150 \"While some people were offering morning prayer at Quba' a man came to them and said, \"A Quranic Order has been revealed to Allah's Apostle tonight that he should face the Ka'ba at Mecca (in prayer), so you too should turn your faces towards it.\" At that moment their faces were towards Sham (i.e. Jerusalem) (and on hearing that) they turned towards the Ka'ba (at Mecca).\" - Sahih Bukhari 6:17 However, the non-muslim sources, Doctrina Iacobi (written between 634-640 AD) and the Armenian Chronicle, also called the Armenian History (written in 660 AD) states otherwise. The arabs and Jews had a good relationship with each other until years after Muhammad died. Adam was the first to place the black stone According to the Islamic traditions Adam placed the black stone in the original Kaaba, while Abraham and Ishmael rebuilt the Meccan Kaaba centuries later. Adam and Eve had their first glance on the Black Stone when it fell from Jannah, showing where to built an altar. According to Islamic tradition, this is the world's first temple. The muslims also believe that the stone has turned black because of people's sins, of those who touched it. It was originally pure and dazzling white, according to them. \"And [mention] when We made the House a place of return for the people and [a place of] security. And take, [O believers], from the standing place of Abraham a place of prayer. And We charged Abraham and Ishmael, [saying], \"Purify My House for those who perform Tawaf and those who are staying [there] for worship and those who bow and prostrate [in prayer].\" And [mention] when Abraham said, \"My Lord, make this a secure city and provide its people with fruits - whoever of them believes in Allah and the Last Day.\" [ Allah ] said. \"And\n\n38\n\nwhoever disbelieves - I will grant him enjoyment for a little; then I will force him to the punishment of the Fire, and wretched is the destination.\" And [mention] when Abraham was raising the foundations of the House and [with him] Ishmael, [saying], \"Our Lord, accept [this] from us. Indeed You are the Hearing, the Knowing.\" - Quran 2:125-127 Since Adam and Eve were the first people on Earth, that means that Mecca is the oldest city on the planet, according to the Quran and Islamic traditions. However no archaeological findings have been found before the 9th century in Mecca. In the construction industry, when a new building has to be built, archaeologists first have to check for any archaeological finds before constructing the foundation of a building - and this happens often in the Middle-East when new buildings have to be build, where something new has been recovered from the ground. This also happens in Saudi Arabia where developers are digging over all putting up great buildings. In Mecca, of all the buildings which were built there, none has come up with an archaeological find. No evidence for ruins of a great ancient city. This would make it very strange because any other city - older according to Islamic tradition - has artefacts and buildings dug up. The older a city is, the more likely there are many things to uncover. And yet, nothing has come up from the city's ground. Mecca is described as the “mother of cities” According to the Quran, and the Islamic traditions, Mecca (or Bakkah) is called the mother of cities. \"And thus We have revealed to you an Arabic Qur'an that you may warn the Mother of Cities [Makkah] and those around it and warn of the Day of Assembly, about which there is no doubt. A party will be in Paradise and a party in the Blaze.\" - Quran 42:7 \"And this is a Book which We have sent down, blessed and confirming what was before it, that you may warn the Mother of Cities and those around it. Those who believe in the Hereafter believe in it, and they are maintaining their prayers.\" Quran 6:92 \"In his hands lay all the dignities of Mecca; he divided the town into quarters among his people and he settled all the Quraysh into their houses in Mecca which they held\" - The Life of Muhammad - A Translation of Ishaq's Sirat Rasul Allah (A. Guillaume), page 53\n\n39\n\nIf Mecca was the mother of cities, there should be archaeological evidence to support this, or any reference from sources about Mecca's importance about being an important city. However, there are no evidence that Mecca existed or was an important city in the Arabian peninsula before 700 AD, except inscriptions. Mecca is described as the center of the trade route Since Adam and Eve were the first people, and it is called the mother of all cities, and now the center of trade center of the trade route, it is puzzling why there is no evidence for that. \"The Prophet said, \"Allah has made Mecca a sanctuary (sacred place) and it was a sanctuary before me and will be so after me.\" - Sahih al-Bukhari 23:432 In Ishaq, page 79, caravans are mentioned going in and out of the Holy City, and same with Muhammad's uncle Abu Talib ibn Abd al-Muttalib, who regularly sent caravans on trading missions. In Ishaq, page 82, Muhammad married Khadija bint Khuwaylid who managed caravans of camels. However, no trade route documents from the 2th-7th century mentions Mecca as being in the trade route, therefore it couldn't either be the center of trade route either. According to Dr. Patricia Crone, Mecca was a barren place, and barren places do not make natural halts. She had written the book Meccan Trade: The Rise of Islam, in which she researched the trade route documents from the 2th-7th century, and no trade routes ever went through Mecca. Many academics agree that the \"center of the trade route\" was further north in North Africa or close to Jerusalem, and not at Mecca which was not even a stopping place on the caravan routes.\n\nMecca missing on early maps What is fascinating about it, is that if Mecca was such an important city, the mother of cities and the center of trading routes, then it is problematic because it does not appear on maps in the 6th, 7th, 8th or 9th century AD. It only began to appear at around 900 AD in on maps, which is about 270 years after Muhammad had died. Dan Gibson had gathered many different ancient maps of Arabia, but not even once did he find Mecca on the maps. It doesn't even appear on Ptolomy's maps of Arabia. The mention of Mecca first appears in literature 741 AD (122 years after the Hijra) in the Continuatio Byzantia Arabica. The Meccan valley\n\n40\n\nThe Quran and the hadiths described Mecca as being in a valley \"While they were in this state Abu- Jandal bin Suhail bin 'Amr came from the valley of Mecca staggering with his fetters and fell down amongst the Muslims\" Sahih al-Bukhari 3:891 \"And He it is Who hath withheld men's hands from you, and hath withheld your hands from them, in the valley of Mecca, after He had made you victors over them. Allah is Seer of what ye do.\" - Quran 48:24 (Pickthall)\n\n\"\"O Abraham! Where are you going, leaving us in this valley where there is no person whose company we may enjoy, nor is there anything (to enjoy)?\" She repeated that to him many times, but he did not look back at her Then she asked him, \"Has Allah ordered you to do so?\" He said, \"Yes.\" She said, \"Then He will not neglect us,\" and returned while Abraham proceeded onwards, and on reaching the Thaniya where they could not see him, he faced the Ka'ba, and raising both hands, invoked Allah saying the following prayers: 'O our Lord! I have made some of my offspring dwell in a valley without cultivation, by Your Sacred House (Kaba at Mecca) in order, O our Lord, that they may offer prayer perfectly.\" Sahih al-Bukhari 4:583 (part 1) \"Then she descended from Safa and when she reached the valley, she tucked up her robe and ran in the valley like a person in distress and trouble, till she crossed the valley and reached the Marwa mountain where she stood and started looking, expecting to see somebody, but she could not see anybody.\" - Sahih al-Bukhari 4:583 (part 2) \"When the Prophet performed the Tawaf of the Ka`ba, he did Ramal during the first three rounds and in the last four rounds he used to walk and while doing Tawaf between Safa and Marwa, he used to run in the midst of the rain water passage.\" - Sahih al-Bukhari 2:26:685 (See also Sahih al-Bukhari 2:645, 2:815, 2:820 and 4:227) The problem is that there are no valleys in Mecca, but there are in Petra. In the complete Sahih al-Bukhari 4:583 hadith above and 26:685, they further mentions the Zam-zam water and rainwater passage, but according to the archaeological evidence, there was no natural flow of water at the time in Mecca, and neither today, except that artifical one that has been built. Normally and naturally a water passage runs between two mountains, but according to the hadith above a water passage runs between two mountains - from one mountain to the other mountain,\n\n41\n\nwhich is a rare phenomenon. However, even thought it is a rare phenomenon, there is actually a rain water passage in Petra that runs from one mountain to the other. The Nabateans built a colonnaded street from one side of the mountain to the other side, which people can visit, for following the course of the water to follow a straight line.In Islam, a Muslims duty is to walk between the two mountains called Marwah and Safa alongside the water passage. The problem with Marwah and Safa is that they are not mountains in Mecca, but only two small rocks, which are so small that they are inside a building. In one of the earliest drawings of Mecca and the Kaaba in the 19th century, one can see that there are no water passage between Marwah and Safa rocks. There is scarce rainfall in Mecca \"And [mention] when Abraham said, \"My Lord, make this a secure city and provide its people with fruits - whoever of them believes in Allah and the Last Day.\" [ Allah ] said. \"And whoever disbelieves - I will grant him enjoyment for a little; then I will force him to the punishment of the Fire, and wretched is the destination.\"\" - Quran 2:126 Today the city of Mecca, with high desert temperatures, only averages about 10 cm of rain per year. This is almost nothing to be able to grow any vegetation. The original Holy City had trees and bushes \"Once when I was with the Prophet in Mecca and we went out into one of its districts in the neighbourhood, not a mountain or tree which confronted him failed to say, \"Peace be upon you, Messenger of Allah.\" Tirmidhi and Darimi transmitted it.\" - Al-Tirmidhi hadith 1535 \"When they came to Mecca they saw a town blessed with water and trees and, delighted with it, they settled there\" - The Life of Muhammad - A Translation of Ishaq's Sirat Rasul Allah (A. Guillaume), page 46 \"People assert that the Quraysh were afraid to cut down the trees of the sanctuary in their quarters\" - The Life of Muhammad - A Translation of Ishaq's Sirat Rasul Allah (A. Guillaume), page 53 \"On the Day of the Conquest of Mecca, Allah's Apostle said, \"Allah has made this town a sanctuary. Its thorny bushes should not be cut, its game should not be chased, and its fallen things should not be picked up except by one who would\n\n42\n\nannounce it publicly.\"\" - Sahih al-Bukhari 2:657 These are important references of trees and thorny bushes in Mecca. Dan Gibson has researched and tried to find ancient trees in Mecca in decades, by testing the presence of spores and pollens in undisturbed ancient soil. So far he has found no evidence that trees ever existed in ancient times in the city of Mecca. However in Petra there were and are plenty of trees. The original Holy City had grapes and fruits growing in it \"By Allah, I never saw a prisoner better than Khubaib. By Allah, one day I saw him eating of a bunch of grapes in his hand while he was chained in irons, and there was no fruit at that time in Mecca.\" - Sahih al-Bukhari 4:281 \"And [mention] when Abraham said, \"My Lord, make this a secure city and provide its people with fruits - whoever of them believes in Allah and the Last Day.\" [ Allah ] said. \"And whoever disbelieves - I will grant him enjoyment for a little; then I will force him to the punishment of the Fire, and wretched is the destination.\"\" - Quran 2:126 According to the above, in Mecca there should be grapes and fruits, however without trees as previously stated, there can be no grapes. However, in Petra it is possible. Grass grew in the original Holy City valley \"..His grace upon him and endow him with prophethood would go forth for his affair and journey far afield until he reached the glens of Mecca and beds of its valleys where no house was in sight\" - The Life of Muhammad - A Translation of Ishaq's Sirat Rasul Allah (A. Guillaume), page 105 \"One night the Prophet was unable to sleep and said, \"Would that a righteous man from my companions guarded me tonight.\" Suddenly we heard the clatter of arms, whereupon the Prophet said, \"Who is it?\" It was said, \"I am Sa'd, O Allah's Apostle! I have come to guard you.\" The Prophet then slept so soundly that we heard him snoring. Abu 'Abdullah said: 'Aisha said: Bilal said, \"Would that I but stayed overnight in a valley with Idhkhir and Jalil (two kinds of grass) around me (i.e., in Mecca).\" Then I told that to the Prophet\" - Sahih al-Bukhari 9:337 \"when the Jurhum came to Mecca “they saw a town blessed with water and trees and, delighted with it, they settled there.\" - Ibn Hashim, page 23\n\n43\n\nThe area around Mecca is completely sand and desert, and no natural grass grows. Furthermore there is no evidence to support that the area could have supported grass before. The cave of Hira Now al-Khattāb had so harassed Zayd that he forced him to withdraw to the upper part of Mecca, and he stopped in the mountain of Hirā’, facing the town Ibn Hisham 49 In reality mount Hira is not facing the town of Mecca, but is on the opposite side of Mecca, facing towards the horizon and other cities. But one special holy cave in Petra exists, where the entrance faces the center of Petra. Inside the cave, wall statues with the crescent moon symbol exists. The original Holy City had clay and loam \"My father Ishaq b. Yasar told me that he was told that 'Abdullah went in to a woman that he had beside Amina d. Wahb when he had been working in and the marks of the were on him\" - The Life of Muhammad - A Translation of Ishaq's Sirat Rasul Allah (A. Guillaume), page 69. See also Al-Tabari VI 1079, page 6. From Al-labar's The History of Al-labar, Volume VI, 1079, page 6, he relates how Abdullah, the father of Muhammad, had been working in the soil, and then traces of soil were still on his hands when he wanted to lie with his second wife in the bed. The second wife made him wait for this, so he went out and washed off the clay and then went to Aminah instead in which Muhammad was born this way. All biographies of Muhammad mentions this story of how Muhammed was born. In Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies, xxi, 1958, pages 1-14, R. B. Serjeant commented on the translation of Alfred Guillaume’s of the same story in the Sirah (which can be read above), and is confused by the Arabic word. The Arabic word is translated to cultivated plot or field, and refers to clay, heavy soil, and loam. The problem is that there is no cultivable land near Mecca, but in Petra there is. He writes that there are no cultivable land in Mecca or near Mecca. This is not the description of what archaeologists have found. Mecca’s mountains does not fit with the descriptions In The Life of Muhammad - A Translation of Ishaq's Sirat Rasul Allah (A. Guillaume), page 25-26, it describes that people could look down from mountains surrounding the Holy City, seeing Yemeni elephant attacking the Kaaba. This indicates that mountains were close enough to the Kaaba to see the details. In\n\n44\n\nMecca there are small outcropping of rocks about 500 meter away. These are the closest, and the second closest are 3 km or further away. It is hard to see an elephant that far. The two mountains called Marwar and Bafa are so small, that they are enclosed inside a mosque. In the mosque there is a long hallway to leads directly between those two rocks. \"The Apostle of Allāh (peace be upon him) came and entered Mecca, and after the Apostle of Allāh (peace be upon him) had gone forward to the stone, and touched it, he went round the house (the Ka'ba). He then went to as-Safa and climbed it so that he could look down at the house. Then he raised his hands began to make mention of Allāh as much as he wished and make supplication. The narrator said: The Ansārwere beneath him. The narrator Hashim said: He prayed and praised Allāh and asked him for what he wished to ask.\" - Sunan of Abū Dawood 750 \"Ar-Rabi’ibn Saburah said on the authority of his father (Saburah): We went out along with the Apostle of Allāh (peace be upon him) till we reached Usfan, Suraqah ibn Mālik al-Mudlaji said to him: Apostle of Allāh, explain to us like the people as if they were born today. He said: Allāh, the exalted, hasincluded this umrah in your Hajj. When you come (to Mecca), and he who goes round the house (the Ka'ba), and runs between as-Safa and al-Marwah, is allowed to take off Ihrām except he who has brought the sacrificial animals with him.\" - Sunan of Abū Dawood 727 \"And when he (Muhammad) reached Mecca on the 4th of Dhūal-Hijja he performed the tawāf round the Ka'ba and performed á'awaf between Safa and Marwa.\" - Sahih al-Bukhari 2:617 According to the Islamic traditions, Bafa and Marwa are not described as two little hllocks within a shallow valley, but rather mountains on both sides of a large valley. This is however not a decription of Mecca, since but fits the description of Petra. Interestingly enough in the next hadith, it mentions that Hagar struggled to cross the valley between the two mountains: \"Hagar sat under the tree with her baby next to her. She drank from her water container hanging nearby, and nursed her baby, until all the water she had was gone, her milk dried out. Her son grew hungrier and hungrier. She could hardly bear to look at him. She went and stood at bafa - the mountain nearest to her. She looked down the valley to see if there was someone around to help. She could see no one. So, she climbed down bafa and reached the valley. She struggled\n\n45\n\nhard, crossed the valley and reached Marwah. She stood on Marwah, and looked around. Still she could see no one around. She repeated this seven times. Ibn ’Abbs added, “The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: ’It is (to commemorate this walk) that pilgrims walk between bafa and Marwah.’”\" - Fiqh us-Sunnah 5:85 In the description above it sounds like the description of the two mountains are large, but in reality, Bafa and Marwah are two small rocks in Mecca. In the next hadith, it described that the Bafa mountain is used as a defence lockout position. “When the Verse: 'And warn your tribe of near kindred.' (26:214) was revealed. Allah's Apostle went out, and when he had ascended As-Safa mountain, he shouted, \"O Sabahah!\" The people said, \"Who is that?\" \"Then they gathered around him, whereupon he said, \"Do you see? If I inform you that cavalrymen are proceeding up the side of this mountain, will you believe me?\" They said, \"We have never heard you telling a lie.\" Then he said, \"I am a plain warner to you of a coming severe punishment.\" Abu Lahab said, \"May you perish! You gathered us only for this reason? \" Then Abu Lahab went away. So the \"Surat: ul-Lahab\" 'Perish the hands of Abu Lahab!' (111:1) was revealed.\" - Sahih al-Bukhari 6:495 In the next hadith, it is written that there were idols on Bafa and Marwah. \"bafa and Marwah as they used to do in the days of Jahiliyya while two idols were set on top of bafa and Marwah.\" - Fiqh us-Sunnah 5:86 \"’Amr set up an image on al-bafa called Nahlik Mujawid al-Rih and one on alMarwa called Mut’im al-Tayr.\" - Isaq 56, page 30 There are no evidence to support that this. In the next hadith, the walk between the two mountains was hard, that they could not do that in one day: \"Ahmad says there is no harm in delaying the Sa’i after performing tawāf until one is rested, or postponing it until evening. ‘Ataand al-Hasan also see no harm in someone making tawāf early in the day and postponing the Sa’i between Safa and Marwah until evening. Al-Qāsim and Sa'īd bin Jubair followed this, because the continuity of Sa’i is, as such, nota condition, much less the continuity of tawāf and Sa’i. Sa'īd bin Mansūr reported that Saudah, the wife of ‘Urwah bin al-Zubair performed Sa’iin between Safa and Marwah and because she was a big and heavy woman, she completed it in three days.\" - Fiqh us-Sunnah 5:88a \"Climbing bafa and Marwah and making supplications for one’s material and\n\n46\n\nspiritual well being and welfare is encouraged. During the supplications one should face the Ka’ba. It is well known that the Prophet (peace be upon him) went through the bafa Gate, and on approaching bafa he recited the Qur'nic verse 2.158 “Verily, bafa and Marwah are among the symbols of Allh” and then saying “I begin with what Allh himself began” he climbed bafa until he could see the Ka’ba from where he stood. He faced the Ka’ba, thrice proclaimed Allh’s oneness, glorified him, praised him, and then said, “There is no deity worthy of worship except Allh. He has no partners. To him belongs the kingdom and all praise. He alone grants life and causes death, he has power over all things. There is no God but he. He has fulfilled his promise, given victory to his servant, and he alone defeated the confederates.” Thrice he made similar supplications. Then he walked toward Marwah and climbed it, until he could see the Ka’ba. There he made supplications as he had at bafa.\" - Fiqh us-Sannah 5:90 What is interesting with 5:90 above is that it tells that there is a Bafa gate. Now this is very strange, because there are no gates in the two small rocks in Mecca. Mecca has a high and low side, together with a road from either side \"During the year of the Conquest (of Mecca), the Prophet entered Mecca through its upper part through Kada.\" - Sahih al-Bukhari 5:586 \"Allah's Apostle used to enter Mecca from the high Thaniya and used to leave Mecca from the low Thaniya.\" - Sahih al-Bukhari 2:645 \"The Prophet went on advancing till he reached the Thaniyya (i.e. a mountainous way) through which one would go to them (i.e. people of Quraish).\" - Sahih alBukhari 3:891 A thaniya is a narrow mountain pass. \"When the Prophet came to Mec"
